int-out-he-has-to-prove-why-the-meeting-cant-be-held-online/articleshow/132541282.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-21T21:37:06+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI World Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132541289,imgsize-168080.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[Scientists studying bee brains found how colonies coordinate without a central controller]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132534955.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[Honeybee colonies organise work without any leader assigning tasks, but scientists have now discovered that specific brain circuits help control this process. By changing the activity of a gene-linked neural circuit, researchers made older worker bees return to caring for the queen, a job usually done only by younger bees. The findings offer new insight into how bees coordinate complex social behaviour.]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/science/scientists-studying-bee-brains-found-clues-to-how-colonies-coordinate-complex-behaviour-without-a-central-controller-relying-instead-on-many-small-individual-decisions/articleshow/132534955.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/science/scientists-studying-bee-brains-found-clues-to-how-colonies-coordinate-complex-behaviour-without-a-central-controller-relying-instead-on-many-small-individual-decisions/articleshow/132534955.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-21T22:00:00+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI Science Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132538708,imgsize-313438.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ex-UK minister Ann Widdecombe was hit 21 times with hammer as she ate lunch, court told]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="marg